But how doth all this confute Servetus's Charge? For whatever Differences there might be between Calvin and the Papists in some Things, yet, why might he not write to the Papists at Vienne to put Servetus to Death for what was equally counted Heresy by them both, and when they agreed as the most intimate Friends and Companions in the Lawfulness of putting Hereticks to Death. What Calvin says of the Absurdity of an Intimacy and Conspiracy with him their mortal Enemy, is no Absurdity at all. Herod and Pontius Pilate, tho' Enemies, agreed in the Condemnation of the Son of God.
